<p>
Packages that need to be produced
</p>

<ul>
<li>any of the libs in /lib or /usr/lib that aren't currently packaged need to be</li>
<li>base-passwd is desperately unhappy</li>
<li>equivilents of console-tools/data need to be produced</li>
<li>netbase needs to be rebuilt. This is probably one of the more awkward ones - we have source for the BSD versions of ifconfig et al, but the semantics are somewhat different. If we stick with BSD semantics, we have to deal with any scripts that assume Linux-style semantics. Does HURD follow Linux-style semantics, and if not how have they dealt with this?</li>
<li>procps (probably best to just provide the BSD versions)</li>
<li>shadow (sort of working, but NetBSD has interesting binary files for dealing with passwords. As a result, stuff like passwd and adduser are not currently as useful as they could be. Somebody needs to look into this)</li>
<li>sysklogd</li>
<li>sysvinit (BSD init doesn't support runlevels. We can hack it to work like Debian with a single runlevel without too much trouble)</li>
</ul>

